The preceding is a list of ITSM skills with entities.  The skills represent the actions available for a customer to request.   The entities represent the types of information that would be important to the processing of that customer request.  If an entity has ‘Required-values’ this indicates that only the values listed can be matched to that entity.

In this use case the term slot refers to the different details associated with an entity.  Some examples are slot-name, slot-description, and slot-required-values.  For slot-required-values, the entity value returned must be either one of the listed values or match the regex pattern.

Your task is to match the customer inquiry below with as many skills as can be identified.  When you return the selected skills, you also need to return any relevant entities and their corresponding values. If no entity value is found, populate that entity value with “None”. If no entity is associated with a skill, return the following as the entity identifier - 0aaaa0a000000aa00 and populate that entity value with “None”.

Your output should be in JSON as noted in the following example.  If there are multiple skills to be returned, then place all of them in the same json output.

For the below examples “<>” means the actual value (“<slot_id>” = “abc123”) while just having quotes means the literal value (“slot_id” = “slot_id”)

{
    "<intent1_id>": [
    {"slot_id": "<slot_id1>", "slot_value": "<slot_value1>"},
    {"slot_id": "<slot_id2>", "slot_value": "<slot_value2>"}
]
}


